# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bidirectional-typing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] In computing, **compile time** is the period of time when a compiler processes source code into other code that is more readily executable – typically object code or byte code.
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] Compile time is a phase in the operational life cycle of a program as it transitions from development to execution.
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] The length of time it takes to compile is usually referred to as *compilation time* although *compile time* might also be used.
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] Compile time can be subdivided by the phases of a compiler.
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] Most compilers have at least the following phases: syntax analysis, semantic analysis, and code generation.
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] Many compilers include one or more optimization phases.
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] For example, each constant expressions might be evaluated via compile-time execution to produce a value that results in improved runtime performance.
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] Properties of a program that can be determined at compile time include range-checks (e.g., proving that an array index will not exceed the array bounds), deadlock freedom in concurrent languages, or timings (e.g., proving that a sequence of code takes no more than an allocated amount of time).
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] For statically-typed languages such as C++, Java or Rust, types are checked at compile time to ensure type safety.
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] Compiling is typically part of a build process (at build time).
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] A build may also include linking (at link time).
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] Run time is the duration when the program is running.
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] Often, compilation occurs as a separate step before running a program.
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] But with dynamic compilation, transformation to machine language happens as part of the process of running it – intertwining run time and compile time.
[src:bidirectional-typing/compile-time] Often this is split into two distinct processes: a build-time process that converts source code to an intermediate representation (IR) and a run-time process that converts the IR to machine code.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] In computer science, **higher-order abstract syntax** (abbreviated **HOAS**) is a technique for the representation of abstract syntax trees for languages with variable binders.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] An abstract syntax is *abstract* because it is represented by mathematical objects that have certain structure by their very nature.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] For instance, in *first-order abstract syntax* (*FOAS*) trees, as commonly used in compilers, the tree structure implies the subexpression relation, meaning that no parentheses are required to disambiguate programs (as they are, in the concrete syntax).
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] HOAS exposes additional structure: the relationship between variables and their binding sites.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] In FOAS representations, a variable is typically represented with an identifier, with the relation between binding site and use being indicated by using the *same* identifier.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] With HOAS, there is no name for the variable; each use of the variable refers directly to the binding site.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] There are a number of reasons why this technique is useful.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] First, it makes the binding structure of a program explicit: just as there is no need to explain operator precedence in a FOAS representation, there is no need to have the rules of binding and scope at hand to interpret a HOAS representation.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] Second, programs that are alpha-equivalent (differing only in the names of bound variables) have identical representations in HOAS, which can make equivalence checking more efficient.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] One mathematical object that could be used to implement HOAS is a graph where variables are associated with their binding sites via edges.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] Another popular way to implement HOAS (in, for example, compilers) is with de Bruijn indices.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] The first programming language which directly supported λ-bindings in syntax was the higher-order logic programming language λProlog.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] The paper that introduced the term HOAS used λProlog code to illustrate it.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] Unfortunately, when one transfers the term HOAS from the logic programming to the functional programming setting, that term implies the identification of bindings in syntax with functions over expressions.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] In this latter setting, HOAS has a different and problematic sense.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] The term λ-tree syntax has been introduced to refer specifically to the style of representation available in the logic programming setting.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] While different in detail, the treatment of bindings in λProlog is similar to their treatment in logical frameworks, elaborated in the next section.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] In the domain of logical frameworks, the term higher-order abstract syntax is usually used to refer to a specific representation that uses the binders of the meta-language to encode the binding structure of the object language.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] For instance, the logical framework LF has a λ-construct, which has arrow (→) type.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] As an example, consider we wanted to formalize a very primitive language with untyped expressions, a built-in set of variables, and a let construct (`let <var> = <exp> in <exp'>`), which allows to bind variables `var` with definition `exp` in expressions `exp'`.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] Here, `exp` is the type of all expressions and `var` the type of all built-in variables (implemented perhaps as natural numbers, which is not shown).
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] The constant `v` acts as a casting function and witnesses the fact that variables are expressions.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] Finally, the constant `let` represents let constructs of the form `let <var> = <exp> in <exp>`: it accepts a variable, an expression (being bound by the variable), and another expression (that the variable is bound within).
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] In this representation, object level variables do not appear explicitly.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] The constant `let` takes an expression (that is being bound) and a meta-level function `exp` → `exp` (the body of the let).
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] This function is the *higher-order* part: an expression with a free variable is represented as an expression with *holes* that are filled in by the meta-level function when applied.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] where `[y] e` is Twelf's syntax for the function $\lambda y.e$ .
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] This specific representation has advantages beyond the ones above: for one, by reusing the meta-level notion of binding, the encoding enjoys properties such as type-preserving *substitution* without the need to define/prove them.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] In this way using HOAS can drastically reduce the amount of boilerplate code having to do with binding in an encoding.
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] Higher-order abstract syntax is generally only applicable when object language variables can be understood as variables in the mathematical sense (that is, as stand-ins for arbitrary members of some domain).
[src:bidirectional-typing/higher-order-abstract-syntax] This is often, but not always, the case: for instance, there are no advantages to be gained from a HOAS encoding of dynamic scope as it appears in some dialects of Lisp because dynamically scoped variables do not act like mathematical variables.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] In computer science, a **local variable** is a variable that is given *local scope*.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] A local variable reference in the function or block in which it is declared overrides the same variable name in the larger scope.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] In programming languages with only two levels of visibility, local variables are contrasted with global variables.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] On the other hand, many ALGOL-derived languages allow any number of nested levels of visibility, with private variables, functions, constants and types hidden within them, either by nested blocks or nested functions.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Local variables are fundamental to procedural programming, and more generally modular programming: variables of local scope are used to avoid issues with side-effects that can occur with global variables.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Local variables may have a lexical or dynamic scope, though lexical (static) scoping is far more common.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] By contrast, in dynamic scoping (or dynamic scope), if a variable name's scope is a certain block, then its scope is that block and all functions transitively called by that block (except when overridden again by another declaration); after the block ends, the variable name does not exist.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Some languages, like Perl and Common Lisp, allow the programmer to choose static or dynamic scoping when defining or redefining a variable.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Examples of languages that use dynamic scoping include Logo, Emacs lisp, and the shell languages bash, dash, and the MirBSD Korn shell (mksh)'s "local" declaration.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Most other languages provide lexically scoped local variables.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] In most languages, local variables are automatic variables stored on the call stack directly.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] This means that when a recursive function calls itself, local variables in each instance of the function are given distinct addresses.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Hence variables of this scope can be declared, written to, and read, without any risk of side-effects to functions outside of the block in which they are declared.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Programming languages that employ *call by value* semantics provide a called subroutine with its own local copy of the arguments passed to it.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] In most languages, these local parameters are treated the same as other local variables within the subroutine.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] In contrast, *call by reference* and *call by name* semantics allow the parameters to act as aliases of the values passed as arguments, allowing the subroutine to modify variables outside its own scope.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] A special type of local variable, called a *static local,* is available in many mainstream languages (including C/C++, Visual Basic, VB.NET and PHP) which allows a value to be retained from one call of the function to another – it is a static variable with local scope.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] In this case, recursive calls to the function also have access to the (single, statically allocated) variable.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] In all of the above languages, static variables are declared as such with a special *storage class* keyword (e.g., `static`).
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Static locals in global functions have the same lifetime as static global variables, because their value remains in memory for the life of the program, but have function scope (not global scope), as with automatic local variables.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] This is distinct from other usages of the `static` keyword, which has several different meanings in various languages.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Perl supports both dynamic and lexically-scoped local variables.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] The keyword `local` is used to define local dynamically-scoped variables, while `my` is used for local lexically-scoped variables.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Since dynamic scoping is less common today, the Perl documentation warns that "`local` isn't what most people think of as “local”.".
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Instead, the `local` keyword gives a temporary, dynamically-scoped value to a global (package) variable, which lasts until the end of the enclosing block.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] However, the variable is visible to any function called from within the block.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] To create lexically-scoped local variables, use the `my` operator instead.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] This happens since the global variable $a is modified to a new *temporary* (local) meaning inside `f()`, but the global value is restored upon leaving the scope of `f()`.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Using `my` in this case instead of `local` would have printed 1 three times since in that case the `$a` variable would be limited to the static scope of the function `f()` and not seen by `g()`.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Schwartz and Tom Phoenix argue that the operator `local` should have had a different name like `save`.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] Note that Ruby only provides built-in support for statically-scoped local variables like Perl's `my`, not dynamically-scoped local variables like Perl's `local`.
[src:bidirectional-typing/local-variable] There is at least one library for Ruby that provides dynamically-scoped variables.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] The term is usually applied to analysis performed by an automated tool, with human analysis typically being called "program understanding", program comprehension, or code review.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] In the last of these, software inspection and software walkthroughs are also used.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] In most cases the analysis is performed on some version of a program's source code, and, in other cases, on some form of its object code.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] The discipline of static analysis should not be confused with linting, which is the process of checking for coding style mistakes.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] The sophistication of the analysis performed by tools varies from those that only consider the behaviour of individual statements and declarations, to those that include the complete source code of a program in their analysis.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] The uses of the information obtained from the analysis vary from highlighting possible coding errors (e.g., the lint tool) to formal methods that mathematically prove properties about a given program (e.g., its behaviour matches that of its specification).
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] Software metrics and reverse engineering can be described as forms of static analysis.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] Deriving software metrics and static analysis are increasingly deployed together, especially in creation of embedded systems, by defining so-called *software quality objectives*.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] A growing commercial use of static analysis is in the verification of properties of software used in safety-critical computer systems and locating potentially vulnerable code.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] Nuclear software: In the UK the Office for Nuclear Regulation (ONR) recommends the use of static analysis on reactor protection systems.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] Aviation software (in combination with dynamic analysis).
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] Automotive & Machines (functional safety features form an integral part of each automotive product development phase, ISO 26262, section 8).
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] A study in 2012 by VDC Research reported that 28.7% of the embedded software engineers surveyed use static analysis tools and 39.7% expect to use them within 2 years.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] A study from 2010 found that 60% of the interviewed developers in European research projects made at least use of their basic IDE built-in static analyzers.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] However, only about 10% employed an additional other (and perhaps more advanced) analysis tool.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] In the application security industry the name static application security testing (SAST) is also used.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] SAST is an important part of Security Development Lifecycles (SDLs) such as the SDL defined by Microsoft and a common practice in software companies.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] The OMG (Object Management Group) published a study regarding the types of software analysis required for software quality measurement and assessment.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] This document on "How to Deliver Resilient, Secure, Efficient, and Easily Changed IT Systems in Line with CISQ Recommendations" describes three levels of software analysis.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes place within a specific program or subroutine, without connecting to the context of that program.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes into account the interactions between unit programs, but without being limited to one specific technology or programming language.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] A further level of software analysis can be defined.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes into account the business/mission layer terms, rules and processes that are implemented within the software system for its operation as part of enterprise or program/mission layer activities.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] These elements are implemented without being limited to one specific technology or programming language and in many cases are distributed across multiple languages, but are statically extracted and analyzed for system understanding for mission assurance.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] Many static analysis tools use intermediate representations of programs to examine the structure of source code without executing the program.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] For this purpose, abstract syntax trees (ASTs) are commonly used, since they provide a structured representation of a program's syntactic elements.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] Formal methods is the term applied to the analysis of software (and computer hardware) whose results are obtained purely through the use of rigorous mathematical methods.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] The mathematical techniques used include denotational semantics, axiomatic semantics, operational semantics, and abstract interpretation.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] This result dates from the works of Church, Gödel and Turing in the 1930s (see: Halting problem and Rice's theorem).
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] As with many undecidable questions, one can still attempt to give useful approximate solutions.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] Data-driven static analysis leverages extensive codebases to infer coding rules and improve the accuracy of the analysis.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] For instance, one can use all Java open-source packages available on GitHub to learn good analysis strategies.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] The rule inference can use machine learning techniques.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] It is also possible to learn from a large amount of past fixes and warnings.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] For certain types of warnings, it is possible to design and implement automated remediation techniques.
[src:bidirectional-typing/static-program-analysis] For example, Logozzo and Ball have proposed automated remediations for C# *cccheck*.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-checking] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] In computer science, a **type signature** or **type annotation** defines the inputs and outputs of a function, subroutine or method.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] A type signature includes the number, types, and order of the function's arguments.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] One important use of a type signature is for function overload resolution, where one particular definition of a function to be called is selected among many overloaded forms.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] In C and C++, the type signature is declared by what is commonly known as a function prototype.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Notice that the type of the result can be regarded as everything past the first supplied argument.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] This is a consequence of currying, which is made possible by Haskell's support for first-class functions; this function requires two inputs where one argument is supplied and the function is "curried" to produce a function for the argument not supplied.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Thus, calling `f x`, where `f :: a -> b -> c`, yields a new function `f2 :: b -> c` that can be called `f2 b` to produce `c`.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] The actual type specifications can consist of an actual type, such as `Integer`, or a general type variable that is used in parametric polymorphic functions, such as `a`, or `b`, or `anyType`.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Since Haskell supports higher-order functions, functions can be passed as arguments.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] This function takes in a function with type signature `a -> a` and returns data of type `a` out.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] In the Java virtual machine, *internal type signatures* are used to identify methods and classes at the level of the virtual machine code.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Example: The method `String String.substring(int, int)` is represented in bytecode as `Ljava/lang/String.substring(II)Ljava/lang/String;` .
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] A function signature consists of the function prototype.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] It specifies the general information about a function like the name, scope and parameters.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Many programming languages use name mangling in order to pass along more semantic information from the compilers to the linkers.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] In addition to mangling, there is an excess of information in a function signature (stored internally to most compilers) which is not readily available, but may be accessed.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Understanding the notion of a function signature is an important concept for all computer science studies.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] The practice of multiple inheritance requires consideration of the function signatures to avoid unpredictable results.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Computer science theory, and the concept of polymorphism in particular, make much use of the concept of function signature.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] In the C programming language, a signature is roughly equivalent to its prototype definition.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] In the ML family of programming languages, "signature" is used as a keyword referring to a construct of the module system that plays the role of an interface.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] In computer programming, especially object-oriented programming, a method is commonly identified by its unique **method signature**, which usually includes the method name and the number, types, and order of its parameters.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] A method signature is the smallest type of a method.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] In C, the method signature is the method name and the number and type of its parameters, but it is possible to have variadic parameters, but these are not type-safe.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Manipulation of these parameters can be done by using the routines in the standard library header `<stdarg.h>`.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] In C++, in addition to the C-style function return type appearing before, the return type may also follow the parameter list, which is referred to as a trailing return type.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] The difference is only syntactic; in either case, the resulting signature is identical.
