[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] In Java, a method signature is composed of a name and the number, type, and order of its parameters.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Return types and thrown exceptions are not considered to be a part of the method signature, nor are the names of parameters; they are ignored by the compiler for checking method uniqueness.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] The method signatures help distinguish overloaded methods (methods with the same name) in a class.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Return types are not included in overloading.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Only method signatures should be used to distinguish overloaded methods.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Variadic parameters in Java are represented with ellipses on the final parameter.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] These behave identically to an array, but in the JVM bytecode the method is marked variadic.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] The types in the arguments are used for the multiple dispatch.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] The return type is validated when the function returns a value, and a runtime exception is raised if the type of the value does not agree with the specified type.
[src:bidirectional-typing/type-signature] Abstract types are allowed and are encouraged for implementing general behavior that is common to all subtypes.
